ss of <i>-r-</i>.","Americanized form of German   Masch  , in part of Sorbian origin.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): possibly an acronymic surname."]},{"name":"Masch","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Erwin, Horst, Ralf.  Jewish Ber, Sima.","North German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>masch</i> ‘marsh, fen’, a variant of <i>marsch</i>. Compare English   Marsh  .","German (Alemannic; <b>Mäsch</b>): nickname from Middle High German <i>mast</i> ‘fat, stout’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":34,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":43,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":54,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":70,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":72,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William John Marsh was born about 1515, in Haverhill, Suffolk, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Mary Ann Milborne. He died in 1591, in Haverhill, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 77."},"et":{"Abt 1515–1591":"umbes 1515–1591","1520–1591":"1520–1591","1535–1578":"1535–1578","1515–1591":"1515–1591","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1578":"1578","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1591":"1591","Abt 1515":"umbes 1515","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Haverhill, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Haverhill, Suffolk, Ing